  "text": "Let us replace u by u/v in (2), and denote H(u, v) = G (u/v, v) . The functional equation becomes: Linear equations with two catalytic variables do not only occur in the enumeration of pattern-avoiding permutations. It happens quite often that the objects one wishes to count admit a recursive description that forces us to keep track of certain secondary statistics (in addition to the size of the objects). If there are two secondary statistics, then the enumeration of the objects is likely to be governed by an equation with two catalytic variables. In particular, planar walks confined in a quadrant provide a wide class of such equations (in this case, the secondary statistics are the coordinates of the endpoint). It was recently shown that, depending on the steps the walk is allowed to take, the associated generating function can be algebraic, D-finite but transcendental 2 , or even non-D-finite [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . This is in sharp contrast to the case of a single catalytic variable, which invariably yields algebraic solutions.",
